[Student "S"]
{Balanced, 17 points. You open 1NT. Partner's response is 2\C.  

Partner's 2\C is Stayman. You have no 4-card Major to show so you bid 2\D. Partner now says 3NT and you pass.

North plays 3NT. East leads \SQ.

<b>North plays 3NT. East leads \SQ.</b>

Winners: \S 2 : \H 0 : \D 4 : \C 2 : Total = 8

The only thing better than being good is being lucky! You are very lucky that you didn't get a \H lead - now you must take advantage of your good luck.

You only need one more winner, and the \C suit is your best bet. You can finesse either defender for the \CQ so naturally you will finesse East. You dare not let East get into the lead since he can lead through dummy's \HK. If West gets the lead with the \CQ, he cannot hurt you.

Win the first trick with the \SA. (<b>DO NOT HOLD UP, EAST MAY SWITCH</b>). Play the \CK then \CJ, letting it ride if not covered. West can win the \CQ but cannot lead a \H without giving you a trick. You win whatever else he returns and make your 9 tricks. Of course you must be careful to unblock the \D A K Q while you still have a dummy entry to the \DJ.

This is another hand where you want to keep a particular defender off lead. In this hand it is East who is the Danger hand.

Be on the lookout for this type of situation because many times you have a finesse that can be made either way. So you finesse into the Safe hand.}
[Play "W"]SQ

[Event ""]
