[Student "S"]
{You estimate your hand has 6 playing tricks. That is reasonable for a preemptive 3\H bid. South overcalls 3\S and partner bids 4\H. Everybody passes.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \SK.

<b>East plays 4\H. South leads the \SK.</b>

Losers: \S 1 : \H 1 : \D 0 : \C 1 : Total = 3

This looks way too easy. If the \H finesse works and the \C finesse works you could make 6. It is when things look too easy that you should look for danger! What if you play the \SA and North ruffs. What if North also gets a trick with the \HK and South gets a trick with the \CQ. What with your \S loser you would be down 1.

South probably has a 7-card suit to overcall at the 3-level, so if you play the \SA North will ruff and one of your winners will disappear. So don't play the \SA. Duck and let South win the trick while North shows out as expected. South will lead the \SQ and you duck again. So South will lead the \SJ and you duck one more time, but now you can ruff in your hand.

Lead your \HQ and finesse, North winning the \HK. North will probably return a \D which you win in dummy. Play the \HA. Then ruff a \D to get back to your hand and pull any trumps left out. Play a \C to dummy's \CA and at long last play dummy's \SA and discard your \C loser.

You always had 10 winners in this hand, as long as one of them didn't disappear.

To make sure the \SA didn't disappear you had to hold it until North no longer had a trump. }
[Play "W"]SK

